    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
    "body" : "<p>What you have should work. If, however, the spaces provided are defaulting to... something else? You can use the whitespace regex:</p>\n<pre><code>str = &quot;Hello I'm your String&quot;;\nString[] splited = str.split(&quot;\\\\s+&quot;);\n</code></pre>\n<p>This will cause any number of consecutive spaces to split your string into tokens.</p>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 998014,
      "reputation" : 801,
      "user_id" : 1013501,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "accept_rate" : 44,
      "profile_image" : "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/4e32a1d909d180aca05623537b8cf1cd?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
      "display_name" : "rbrtl",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/1013501/rbrtl"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 33,
    "last_activity_date" : 1523541731,
    "last_edit_date" : 1523541731,
    "creation_date" : 1319612650,
    "answer_id" : 7899604,
    "question_id" : 7899525,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
    "body" : "<p>I do believe that putting a regular expression in the str.split parentheses should solve the issue. The Java String.split() method is based upon regular expressions so what you need is:</p>\n\n<pre><code>str = \"Hello I'm your String\";\nString[] splitStr = str.split(\"\\\\s+\");\n</code></pre>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 3648696,
      "reputation" : 709,
      "user_id" : 3041354,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "profile_image" : "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/08554a1d9f83bbd97683b08b8d35aa1b?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG&f=y&so-version=2",
      "display_name" : "sandeep vanama",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/3041354/sandeep-vanama"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 15,
    "last_activity_date" : 1400681663,
    "last_edit_date" : 1400681663,
    "creation_date" : 1396850349,
    "answer_id" : 22904619,
    "question_id" : 7899525,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
    "body" : "<p>Use <code>Stringutils.split()</code> to split the string by whites paces. For example <code>StringUtils.split(\"Hello World\")</code> returns \"Hello\" and \"World\";</p>\n\n<p>In order to solve the mentioned case we use split method like this </p>\n\n<pre><code>String split[]= StringUtils.split(\"Hello I'm your String\");\n</code></pre>\n\n<p>when we print the split array the output will be :</p>\n\n<p>Hello</p>\n\n<p>I'm</p>\n\n<p>your</p>\n\n<p>String</p>\n\n<p><a href=\"http://java-interview-questions.com/how-to-separate-strings-in-java-by-spaces-with-example\">For complete example demo check here</a></p>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 1283802,
      "reputation" : 4538,
      "user_id" : 1237287,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "accept_rate" : 52,
      "profile_image" : "https://i.sstatic.net/fcwHE.jpg?s=256",
      "display_name" : "gjain",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/1237287/gjain"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 5,
    "last_activity_date" : 1403262610,
    "creation_date" : 1403262610,
    "answer_id" : 24325929,
    "question_id" : 7899525,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
    "body" : "<p>An alternative way would be:</p>\n\n<pre><code>import java.util.regex.Pattern;\n\n...\n\nprivate static final Pattern SPACE = Pattern.compile(\" \");\nString[] arr = SPACE.split(str); // str is the string to be split\n</code></pre>\n\n<p>Saw it <a href=\"https://github.com/apache/spark/blob/master/examples/src/main/java/org/apache/spark/examples/streaming/JavaNetworkWordCount.java\" rel=\"noreferrer\">here</a></p>\n"
  }, {
